05968nam a22010095i 9781479803361DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020015031  a97814798033617 a10.18574/97814798033612doi  a(DE-B1597)551023  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aE184.36.E84 4aE184.36.E84bG76 2021 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a305.8009732231 aGross, Rachel B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond the Synagogue :bJewish Nostalgia as Religious Practice /cRachel B. Gross. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b20 b/w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNorth American Religions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tIntroduction: Feeling Jewish -- t1. How Do You Solve a Problem like Nostalgia? -- t2. Give Us Our Name: Creating Jewish Genealogy -- t3. Ghosts in the Gallery: Historic Synagogues as Heritage Sites -- t4. True Stories: Teaching Nostalgia to Children -- t5. Referendum on the Jewish Deli Menu: A Culinary Revival -- tConclusion: The Limits and Possibilities of Nostalgia -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReveals nostalgia as a new way of maintaining Jewish continuityIn 2007, the Museum at Eldridge Street opened at the site of a restored nineteenth-century synagogue originally built by some of the first Eastern European Jewish immigrants in New York City. Visitors to the museum are invited to stand along indentations on the floor where footprints of congregants past have worn down the soft pinewood. Here, many feel a palpable connection to the history surrounding them.Beyond the Synagogue argues that nostalgic activities such as visiting the Museum at Eldridge Street or eating traditional Jewish foods should be understood as American Jewish religious practices. In making the case that these practices are not just cultural, but are actually religious, Rachel B. Gross asserts that many prominent sociologists and historians have mistakenly concluded that American Judaism is in decline, and she contends that they are looking in the wrong places for Jewish religious activity. If they looked outside of traditional institutions and practices, such as attendance at synagogue or membership in Jewish Community Centers, they would see that the embrace of nostalgia provides evidence of an alternative, under-appreciated way of being Jewish and of maintaining Jewish continuity. Tracing American Jews’ involvement in a broad array of ostensibly nonreligious activities, including conducting Jewish genealogical research, visiting Jewish historic sites, purchasing books and toys that teach Jewish nostalgia to children, and seeking out traditional Jewish foods, Gross argues that these practices illuminate how many American Jews are finding and making meaning within American Judaism today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHomesicknesszEurope, Eastern. 0aJewsxCultural assimilationzUnited States. 0aJewszCultural assimilationzUnited States. 0aJewszUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aJudaismzUnited States. 0aNostalgia. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aPJ Library.  acamp.  achildren’s books.  adeli.  adelis.  adolls.  afood studies.  agenealogy.  ainstitutions.  airony.  alived religion.  amemory.  amuseum studies.  apopular culture.  apublic history.  arestaurant.  asecular.  asynagogue.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08